  "opinion": "As a woman who's spent most of her life in the small town of Bari, Italy, watching my children grow up and see the world change, I've noticed how science has always been a field where men dominate. When I was young, my parents, both who only went to primary school, never spoke much about science— they were more interested in the practical skills of carpentry and farming. But now, I see that the gender gap in science isn't just about numbers; it's about the stories we tell ourselves. Many girls are discouraged from pursuing science early on because they're told it's for boys, or they feel they don't have the 'right' kind of mind. I've seen this in my own community— my daughters, for instance, often say they're not 'good' at math because they were never encouraged to try. But I believe the gap shouldn't be a barrier at all. It's not about changing who we are; it's about changing how we see ourselves. In my creative work, I've found that storytelling can help bridge this divide. When I teach my grandchildren to knit or climb rocks, I often use science concepts to make them feel connected to the natural world. If we can show girls that science is part of their daily lives, not just a distant, male-dominated field, we can start to close this gap. We should address it by creating more inclusive environments where everyone feels they belong—whether it's through community workshops, mentorship programs, or simply talking openly about the barriers we face. The key is to listen, to understand, and to help young girls see themselves as scientists, not as exceptions.",
